# Streaming an LLM completion with lazyhttp
#
# A self-contained demo of `# @stream`: lazyhttp reads the response body as it
# arrives and shows it live, so you watch the model generate token by token in
# the response pane instead of waiting for the whole reply.
#
# The fun twist: the system prompt makes the model answer in "caveman language"
# — the viral telegraphic style (drop articles, drop filler: "ME WANT", "USE FEW
# WORD") that people use to cut LLM output tokens by ~40-60%. So you get a tiny,
# punchy story streaming in, grunt by grunt.
#
# Setup: OpenRouter (https://openrouter.ai) gives access to many models behind
# one OpenAI-compatible API. Create a key and export it before you run —
# `{{$processEnv …}}` reads it at send time, so no secret lives in this file:
#
#   export OPENROUTER_API_KEY=sk-or-...
#   lazyhttp examples/openrouter-stream.http
#
# The raw stream is noisy: keepalive comments (`: OPENROUTER PROCESSING`), the
# `data:` envelope, and a whole JSON object per token. The two steps below each
# distil it down to just the text, so you see the story — not the wire framing.

### Caveman story — built-in field extraction
### `# @stream <jsonpath>` parses the SSE `data:` frames and emits just that
### field, so the response reads as the assembled story. No external tools.
# @group AI
# @name Caveman story (stream + extract)
# @stream choices[0].delta.content
# @timeout 5 m
# @assert status == 200
POST https://openrouter.ai/api/v1/chat/completions
Authorization: Bearer {{$processEnv OPENROUTER_API_KEY}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "model": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4.5",
  "stream": true,
  "messages": [
    { "role": "system", "content": "TALK LIKE CAVEMAN. NO ARTICLE. NO 'THE', NO 'A', NO 'AN'. DROP FILLER WORD. SHORT WORD. GRUNT OK. ME SAVE TOKEN. STILL TELL WHOLE STORY, BEGINNING MIDDLE END." },
    { "role": "user", "content": "Tell story about startup that raise too much money and forget make product. Make it have a funny punchline." }
  ]
}

### Same thing — external command pipe (needs jq)
### `# @stream-through <cmd>` runs the live stream through any shell command via
### stdin→stdout. Here jq strips the `data:` envelope, skips comments and the
### `[DONE]` sentinel, and prints just the delta text. Use this for formats the
### built-in extractor doesn't cover.
# @group AI
# @name Caveman story (stream-through jq)
# @stream-through jq -Rj --unbuffered 'ltrimstr("data: ") | select(startswith("{")) | fromjson | .choices[0].delta.content // empty'
# @timeout 5 m
# @assert status == 200
POST https://openrouter.ai/api/v1/chat/completions
Authorization: Bearer {{$processEnv OPENROUTER_API_KEY}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "model": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4.5",
  "stream": true,
  "messages": [
    { "role": "system", "content": "TALK LIKE CAVEMAN. NO ARTICLE. DROP FILLER WORD. SHORT WORD. GRUNT OK. STILL TELL WHOLE STORY." },
    { "role": "user", "content": "Tell story about engineer who rewrite everything in Rust to avoid one bug. Make it have a funny punchline." }
  ]
}

### For comparison: no transform at all
### Plain `# @stream` shows the raw SSE wire format as it arrives — handy to see
### exactly what the server sends (and why the two steps above are nicer).
# @group AI
# @name Raw stream (no transform)
# @stream
# @timeout 5 m
# @assert status == 200
POST https://openrouter.ai/api/v1/chat/completions
Authorization: Bearer {{$processEnv OPENROUTER_API_KEY}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "model": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4.5",
  "stream": true,
  "messages": [
    { "role": "user", "content": "Say hello in one short sentence." }
  ]
}
